          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">EU sticks with Israel</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">European Union foreign ministers have <a href="https://www.dw.com/en/eu-ministers-reject-suspending-dialogue-with-israel/a-70807176" target="_blank">rejected</a> a proposal by Josep Borrell, the bloc’s foreign policy chief, to suspend diplomatic dialogue with Israel. <a href="https://www.middleeasteye.net/live-blog/live-blog-update/borrell-proposes-suspension-political-dialogue-israel" target="_blank">Borrell</a> has a critical stance on Israel and suggested the move as a response to Israeli actions in Gaza, citing severe humanitarian impacts, which include the deaths of tens of thousands of civilians. The proposal is seen as Borrell’s bold parting move before leaving office. It required unanimous support from the 27 EU member states but faced opposition from nations like Germany, Hungary, Austria, and the Netherlands.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Instead, ministers opted to maintain the EU-Israel dialogue under the Association Agreement, which emphasizes cooperation based on mutual respect for human rights. Meanwhile, Borrell also proposed a <a href="https://www.eeas.europa.eu/eeas/war-gaza-we-cannot-continue-business-usual_en" target="_blank">ban on imports</a> from Israeli settlements, which are illegal under international law, though this measure was not widely discussed. Separately, the ministers approved new sanctions on Iran and supported broader military options for Ukraine. The situation with Ukraine is less polarized in the EU than Israel and Palestine. Most EU nations are more or less on the same page on Ukraine and Iran, likely due to less nuance in these situations. </p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>

