          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>🇷🇺 Russia:</strong>   
          Russian President Vladimir Putin has <a href="https://apnews.com/article/russia-nuclear-doctrine-putin-91f20e0c9b0f9e5eaa3ed97c35789898" target="_blank">lowered</a> the threshold for the use of nuclear weapons, permitting retaliation against conventional attacks from nations supported by nuclear powers. Putin made this decision in response to Ukraine’s <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c0mzjm7knw7o" target="_blank">missile strike</a> on Russia’s <a href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Bryansk+Oblast,+Russia/@52.9331984,31.9655996,8z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!3m5!1s0x46d2d14dcf496edf:0x102a3a583f19610!8m2!3d53.0408599!4d33.26909!16zL20vMDJmNDc5?entry=ttu&g_ep=EgoyMDI0MTExNy4wIKXMDSoASAFQAw%3D%3D" target="_blank">Bryansk</a> region, which the United States approved. The revised doctrine expands the circumstances under which nuclear weapons could be used, drawing condemnation from the West as an act of reckless escalation. However, U.S. officials have reported that there has been no change in Russia’s nuclear posture.</p>
        </mj-text>
